  "debug_data_path": "debug_data/2020_566",
  "eprint": {
    "title": "Reputation Driven Dynamic Access Control Framework for IoT atop PoA Ethereum Blockchain",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Auqib Hamid Lone",
        "email": "ahl@nitsri",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Roohie Naaz",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Security and Scalability are two major challenges that IoT is currently facing. Access control to critical IoT infrastructure is considered as top security\nchallenge that IoT faces. Data generated by IoT devices may be driving\nmany hard real time systems, thus it is of utmost importance to guarantee\nintegrity and authenticity of the data and resources at the first place itself.\nDue to heterogeneous and constrained nature of IoT devices, traditional IoT\nsecurity frameworks are not able to deliver scalable, efficient and manageable mechanisms to meet the requirements of IoT devices. On the other hand\nBlockchain technology has shown great potential to bridge the missing gap\ntowards building a truly decentralized, trustworthy, secure and scalable environment for IoT. Allowing access to IoT resources and data managed through\nBlockchain will provide an additional security layer backed by the strongest\ncryptographic algorithms available. In this work we present a reputation\ndriven dynamic access control framework for small scale IoT applications\nbased on Proof of Authority Blockchain, we name it as Rep-ACM. In RepACM framework we build two major services, one for Reputation building\n(for better IoT device behaviour regulations) and other for Misbehaviour detection (for detecting any Misbehaviour on object resource usage). Both of\nthese services work in coordination with other services of proposed framework to determine who can access what and under what conditions access\nshould be granted. For Proof of Concept (PoC) we created private Ethereum\nnetwork consisting of two Raspberry Pi single board computers, one desktop computer and a laptop as nodes. We configured Ethereum protocol to use\nIstanbul Byzantine Fault Tolerance (IBFT) as Proof of Authority (PoA) consensus mechanism for performance optimization in constrained environment.\nWe deployed our model on private network for feasibility and performance\nanalysis.",
    "keywords": [
      "Reputation",
      "Access Control",
      "IoT",
      "Permissioned Blockchain",
      "Proof of authority"
    ],
    "category": "Applications",
    "publication_info": "Preprint. MINOR revision.",
    "last_updated": "2021-02-21",
    "license": "CC BY",
    "related_papers": []
  }
